window.GD_ASSIST={"lessons":[{"f":"ag-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Agents","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"What an agents interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Agent in one line? · Why a loop? · ReAct? · Planning vs reacting? · Agent memory? · Multi-agent default? · Reliability? · Biggest risk?","s":"Agents are the frontier of applied AI, so interviewers use them to test whether you understand the whole picture: what an agent is (an LLM in an act–observe loop, not just a chatbot), how it uses tools, how it reasons and plans, how it remembers, when to use multiple agents, and — most of all — how to make it reliable and safe ."},{"f":"ag1-what.html","t":"What is an agent","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"From answering to acting · Single call vs pipeline vs agent · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · agent · think → act → observe → repeat · single call · pipeline · agent · least autonomous · agent","s":"So far an LLM has been a function: text in, text out. A single call answers one question; even RAG (Track 8) is one fixed sequence — retrieve, then generate. An agent is different: it's an LLM that decides what to do , takes an action, observes the result, and decides again — looping until it accomplishes a goal. The model is no longer just producing an answer; it's driving a process , choosing its own steps."},{"f":"ag2-tools.html","t":"Function / tool calling","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"How a text model reaches into the world · The tool schema: telling the model what's available · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Tool calling · decides, never executes · schema · description · fine-tuned · tool calling · schema · validate","s":"An LLM only outputs text — so how does it do things: search the web, run code, query a database, send an email? Through tool calling (also called function calling). The mechanism is elegant: you tell the model what tools are available, and when it wants to use one, it doesn't run it — it emits a structured request (typically JSON) naming the tool and its arguments."},{"f":"ag3-react.html","t":"ReAct: reasoning + acting","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"Interleaving thinking and doing · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · ReAct · Thought · Action · Observation · chain-of-thought + tools · trace · default agent pattern · Observation · Thought · Action · ReAct","s":"An agent has a loop (Lesson 9.1) and tools (Lesson 9.2) — but how should it use them across a multi-step problem? The dominant pattern is ReAct (Reasoning + Acting): the model alternates between Thought (reasoning about what to do next), Action (calling a tool), and Observation (reading the tool's result), looping until it has enough to answer."},{"f":"ag4-planning.html","t":"Planning & task decomposition","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"Giving an agent direction: planning · Reflection: catching your own mistakes · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Planning · Reactive · plan-and-execute · re-plan · Reflection · recognizing · grounded · reflection · Planning · Reactive · Plan-and-execute · subtasks","s":"A purely reactive agent (ReAct, Lesson 9.3) decides one step at a time, which is flexible but can wander, lose the thread on a complex goal, or get stuck in loops. Planning adds direction: before diving in, the agent breaks the goal into a sequence of smaller, ordered subtasks — a plan — and then executes them."},{"f":"ag5-memory.html","t":"Memory (short & long-term)","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"Two kinds of memory: working and long-term · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Short-term memory · Long-term memory · summarize · continuity · personalization · store-and-retrieve · context window · long-term memory · short-term memory · summarized","s":"An agent's reasoning, plan, and tool results all live in its context window (Lesson 6.1) — which is its short-term memory , the \"working memory\" it reasons over right now. But the context window is limited (even large ones fill up on long tasks) and it's forgotten when the conversation ends. For agents that run long, or that should remember a user across sessions, that isn't enough."},{"f":"ag6-multiagent.html","t":"Multi-agent patterns","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"Many agents, each with a specialty · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Multi-agent · supervisor/worker · pipeline · debate · modularity · multi-agent · Pipeline · Debate · Supervisor/worker","s":"So far we've had one agent with tools, memory, and a loop. For complex jobs, an alternative is a multi-agent system: several agents, each specialized for a role, coordinating to solve the task together. The intuition is a team — instead of one generalist doing everything, you have a researcher, a writer, a reviewer, each focused on what it does best, with a coordinator orchestrating them."},{"f":"ag7-reliability.html","t":"Guardrails & reliability for agents","tn":"AI Agents","k":"9","x":"An agent that acts can also cause harm · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · act · Permissions · Budgets/limits · Human-in-the-loop · sandboxing · monitoring · defense in depth · dangerous · Guardrails · defense in depth","s":"Everything that makes agents powerful — they take real actions in the world (Lesson 9.1) — also makes them dangerous when they go wrong. A chatbot that hallucinates produces a bad sentence; an agent that hallucinates might delete a file, send a wrong email, spend money, or loop forever burning through your budget. As autonomy goes up, so does the cost of mistakes."},{"f":"cap0-setup.html","t":"Capstone 0: project setup & reproducibility","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"Build a portfolio, prove you can ship · Check yourself · Set up your capstone · capstones · Reproducibility · code · data · environment · seed · config · random seed · project setup and reproducibility · Reproducibility","s":"You've learned the concepts; the capstones are where you prove it by building. This track is a set of end-to-end projects — an image classifier, a fine-tuned LLM, a RAG assistant, an agent, a served API, a full pipeline — that together form a portfolio demonstrating you can build real, working AI systems, not just discuss them."},{"f":"cap1-imageclf.html","t":"Capstone 1: image classifier (transfer learning)","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"The project: a custom image classifier from little data · Check yourself · Build and extend it · custom image classifier · transfer learning · Transfer learning · backbone · head · freeze · default · image classifier · transfer learning · head · backbone","s":"The first capstone is a classic, high-impact project: build an image classifier for a custom task (say, classifying types of flowers, or defective vs good parts, or your own categories) using transfer learning . It's an ideal first project because it's genuinely useful, achievable, and demonstrates a technique used everywhere in practice — and it produces a working model you can show."},{"f":"cap2-finetune-llm.html","t":"Capstone 2: fine-tune a small LLM (LoRA)","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"The project: adapt an LLM to your task, cheaply · Check yourself · Build and reason about it · fine-tune a small LLM · LoRA · LoRA freezes the model · low-rank adapter · update · swap adapters · QLoRA · LoRA · low-rank · fine-tune","s":"This capstone is transfer learning's language analog: take a pretrained language model and fine-tune it to your specific task or style — but efficiently, using LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation). Full fine-tuning of a modern LLM means updating billions of parameters, which needs enormous memory and compute — out of reach for most."},{"f":"cap3-rag.html","t":"Capstone 3: a RAG assistant over your docs","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"The project: an assistant that answers from your knowledge · Check yourself · Build and reason about it · RAG assistant · Offline · Online · current, private, citable · RAG assistant","s":"This capstone builds the most-deployed LLM pattern in production: a RAG assistant that answers questions grounded in your documents — a company knowledge base, a set of manuals, your own notes, any corpus. It's an exceptional portfolio project because RAG is exactly what a huge fraction of real LLM applications are, and building one end to end demonstrates you can turn a pile of documents into a working, grounded question-answering system."},{"f":"cap4-agent.html","t":"Capstone 4: a tool-using agent","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"The project: an LLM that acts, not just answers · Check yourself · Build and reason about it · agent · tools · think → act → observe loop · act · guardrails · independent of the model · guardrails · agent · agent loop","s":"This capstone builds an agent — an LLM that doesn't just respond but acts : it reasons about a goal, calls tools (a calculator, a search, an API, code execution), observes the results, and loops until the task is done. It's a compelling portfolio project because agents are the frontier of applied AI, and building one demonstrates you understand the act–observe loop, tool use, and — critically — the guardrails that make an acting system safe."},{"f":"cap5-serve.html","t":"Capstone 5: ship a monitored model API","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"The project: turn a model into an operable service · Check yourself · Build and reason about it · serving API · monitoring · Serving · Monitoring · you can't operate what you can't see · production skills · monitoring · serving API","s":"A trained model is a file; a product is a service users can call, reliably, that you can watch and maintain. This capstone builds exactly that: wrap a model in a serving API — an endpoint that receives requests and returns predictions — and add the monitoring that makes it operable."},{"f":"cap6-pipeline.html","t":"Capstone 6: full training→serving pipeline","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"The capstone of capstones: automate the whole loop · Check yourself · Build and reflect · full training→serving pipeline · data → train → evaluate → deploy → monitor → retrain · deployment gate · drift · closing the loop · machinery around a model · ML lifecycle loop · gate","s":"The final project brings everything together into one automated system: a full training→serving pipeline that takes data all the way through training, evaluation, deployment, monitoring, and retraining — with as little manual intervention as possible. Where the earlier capstones each built one piece (a model, a served API), this one assembles them into the complete ML lifecycle loop as a running system."},{"f":"cm-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Classical ML","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"What a classical-ML interview is really testing · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Why squared error? · Why sigmoid + cross-entropy? · Generative vs discriminative? · Why standardize? · Curse of dimensionality? · How pick k in k-means?","s":"Knowing the models isn't the same as explaining them under pressure. A classical-ML interview round probes whether you understand why things work, can pick the right tool for a situation, and can reason about tradeoffs out loud. The questions below are the ones that come up again and again — for each, the model answer shows not just the fact but the reasoning , which is what interviewers actually score."},{"f":"cm1-setup.html","t":"The ML problem setup: features, labels, train/test","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"What \"learning from data\" actually means · Your data is a table: a matrix X and a vector y · The whole game is generalization — so you hide some data · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Supervised learning · features · label · generalization · train · validation · test · data leakage · stratified · Unsupervised learning · training set · supervised learning · overfitting · distribution shift · target · machine learning · label · class imbalance · feature matrix · feature","s":"Up to now you've built the tools: vectors, matrices, gradients, NumPy, pandas. Starting here, you use them to do the actual job — machine learning : writing programs that improve at a task by looking at examples, instead of by being told the rules."},{"f":"cm10-clustering.html","t":"Clustering & unsupervised learning","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"Learning without an answer key · k-means: the workhorse clustering algorithm · How many clusters? Choosing k · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Unsupervised learning · clustering · k-means · centroid · k · elbow · silhouette · Standardize · elbow method · silhouette score · clustering · k-means · standardize · inertia · unsupervised learning · centroid","s":"Every model so far was supervised — it learned from labeled examples. Now we drop the labels. In unsupervised learning you have only the inputs X and want to discover structure that's already there, with nobody telling you the \"right\" answer. The most common form is clustering : grouping examples so that points in the same group are similar and points in different groups are not."},{"f":"cm11-dimred.html","t":"Dimensionality reduction (PCA, t-SNE, UMAP)","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"Too many features is its own problem · PCA: rotate to the most informative axes · t-SNE and UMAP: maps made for the eye · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Dimensionality reduction · PCA · explained variance ratio · t-SNE / UMAP · standardize · principal component · Principal Component Analysis · scree plot · curse of dimensionality · t-SNE · Dimensionality reduction · UMAP · explained variance ratio","s":"Real datasets often have dozens, hundreds, or thousands of features. That causes three headaches: you can't visualize more than 3 dimensions; distances become less meaningful in high dimensions (the \" curse of dimensionality \" — everything ends up roughly equidistant); and many features are redundant or noisy, slowing models and inviting overfitting."},{"f":"cm12-modelselection.html","t":"Model selection & cross-validation","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"The problem with a single validation split · k-fold cross-validation · Searching for the best hyperparameters · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · noisy · k-fold cross-validation · stratified · hyperparameters · grid · random search · pipeline · held-out test set · stratified · Cross-validation · hyperparameters · Bayesian optimization · Grid search · random search · k-fold cross-validation","s":"You've used a validation set to make choices since Lesson 3.1. But a single split has a weakness: the score depends on which examples happened to land in that one validation set. Get a lucky split and a mediocre model looks great; get an unlucky one and a good model looks weak. With limited data, that randomness can be larger than the real difference between two models you're trying to compare — so you'd pick the wrong one."},{"f":"cm2-linreg.html","t":"Linear regression from scratch","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"The simplest real model: a straight line · Measuring wrongness: mean squared error · Two routes to the best line · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Linear regression · mean squared error · convex · normal equations · gradient descent · bias · mean squared error · gradient descent · residual · weight · prediction · normal equations · linear regression · convex","s":"The first model in machine learning is the one you already know from school: a straight line. In linear regression we predict a number (a \"continuous\" target like price or temperature) by taking a weighted sum of the features. With one feature it's the line y = w ,x + b , where the prediction is written y (\"y-hat\" — the hat means \"estimated\"), w is the weight (the slope: how much y moves per unit of x ), and b is the bias (the intercept: the prediction when x = 0 )."},{"f":"cm3-logreg.html","t":"Logistic regression & classification","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"From predicting numbers to predicting categories · The decision boundary is a straight line · The loss: cross-entropy, not squared error · More than two classes: softmax · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Logistic regression · sigmoid · threshold · decision boundary · cross-entropy · Softmax · probability · decision boundary · sigmoid · cross-entropy · classification · hyperplane · probability · logistic regression · softmax · class · threshold · convex","s":"Linear regression predicts a number. But a huge fraction of real problems ask a yes/no question instead: is this email spam? is this tumor malignant? will this customer churn? That's classification — predicting which class (category) an example belongs to. We'll start with two classes (binary classification), which we label 0 and 1."},{"f":"cm4-metrics.html","t":"Loss functions & evaluation metrics","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"Why accuracy can be a dangerous lie · The confusion matrix: four outcomes · Precision and recall: two questions, two denominators · The threshold dial, and ROC-AUC · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Accuracy lies · confusion matrix · Precision · recall · F1 · ROC-AUC · real-world cost · AUC · Recall · precision-recall AUC · Precision · F1 score · Accuracy · ROC curve","s":"Accuracy — the fraction of predictions you got right — is the obvious metric, and for balanced problems it's fine. But it collapses the moment one class is rare. Suppose 99.5% of credit-card transactions are legitimate. A model that blindly predicts \"legitimate\" for everything scores 99.5% accuracy while catching exactly zero fraud."},{"f":"cm5-biasvar.html","t":"Bias–variance tradeoff & overfitting","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"Two ways to fail: underfitting and overfitting · The tradeoff: test error is U-shaped in complexity · The decomposition that explains it all · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Underfitting · bias · overfitting · variance · U-shaped · small train–test gap · large gap · bias² + variance + irreducible noise · Bias · Variance · underfitting · overfitting","s":"Every model that disappoints does so in one of two ways, and telling them apart is the most useful diagnostic skill in machine learning. A model can be underfitting — too simple to capture the real pattern, so it's wrong even on the training data (think: a straight line through an obviously curved trend)."},{"f":"cm6-regularization.html","t":"Regularization (L1 / L2)","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"Penalize complexity directly · Why L1 zeros weights but L2 doesn't · The strength dial λ · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Regularization · L2 (ridge) · L1 (lasso) · exactly zero · λ · standardize features · feature selector · Regularization · sparse · L1 regularization · ridge · L2 regularization · lasso","s":"Lesson 3.5 said overfitting comes from a model that's too flexible — and for linear models, \"too flexible\" shows up concretely as large weights . A wildly overfit polynomial has huge coefficients that nearly cancel, producing the violent wiggles we saw. Regularization is the direct cure: add a penalty for big weights to the loss, so the optimizer has to balance fitting the data against keeping weights small."},{"f":"cm7-trees.html","t":"Decision trees","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"A model you could explain to your grandparent · How a tree chooses its questions: impurity · Why a single tree overfits · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · decision tree · leaf · impurity · axis-aligned · no feature scaling · interpretable · overfits · root · axis-aligned · leaf · entropy · decision tree · split · pure · Gini impurity","s":"Every model so far drew a straight boundary. A decision tree works completely differently and more intuitively: it asks a sequence of yes/no questions about the features, like a flowchart, and the answer you land on is the prediction. \"Is the tumor radius &gt; 15? If yes, is the texture &gt; 20? If yes, predict malignant.\" It's the way a person might reason, which is exactly why trees are so easy to interpret."},{"f":"cm8-ensembles.html","t":"Ensembles: Random Forests & Gradient Boosting","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"The wisdom of crowds, for models · Bagging and the Random Forest · Boosting: a team that learns from its mistakes · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · ensemble · Bagging / Random Forest · variance · Boosting · bias · winners on tabular data · Bagging · Random Forest · Boosting · XGBoost · ensemble · LightGBM","s":"A single decision tree is flexible but unstable (high variance). The fix is one of the most powerful and reliable ideas in all of applied machine learning: don't trust one model — train many and combine them. This is an ensemble . If each model is decent and they make different mistakes, averaging their predictions cancels the individual errors while keeping the shared signal, like polling a crowd instead of asking one person."},{"f":"cm9-svm.html","t":"Support Vector Machines","tn":"Classical ML","k":"3","x":"Of all the lines that separate the classes, which is best? · Support vectors: only the borderline points matter · The kernel trick: curved boundaries for free · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · SVM · margin · support vectors · soft margin · C · kernel trick · RBF kernel · support vectors · C · soft margin · kernel trick · kernel · gamma · RBF kernel · margin","s":"Logistic regression finds a line that separates two classes, but when the classes are cleanly separable there are infinitely many such lines — and they're not equally good. A line that skims right past the data points is fragile: a slightly different new point could fall on the wrong side."},{"f":"cv-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Computer Vision","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"What a computer-vision interview tests · Check yourself · Rehearse out loud · The task ladder: · CNN vs ViT = inductive bias vs data: · Diffusion generates by learning to reverse noise: · CLIP aligns image and text · Everything connects:","s":"A computer-vision interview is less about memorizing architectures and more about whether you can match a task to the right tool and justify the trade-offs ."},{"f":"cv1-images.html","t":"How computers see: images as tensors","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"To a computer, an image is just numbers · Data augmentation: more data for free · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · tensor · height × width × 3 · CNNs · spatial structure · Data augmentation · Data augmentation · tensor · computer vision · CNNs","s":"This track is a specialization on computer vision — teaching machines to see — and it builds directly on the neural networks and CNNs of Track 4. The first thing to internalize is that a computer has no notion of a \"picture.\" An image, to a model, is a tensor : a grid of numbers. A color image is a 3D tensor of shape height × width × 3 — for every pixel, three numbers giving its red, green, and blue intensities (each 0–255)."},{"f":"cv2-classification.html","t":"Image classification & CNN architectures","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"Convolution: the operation that sees · Architectures: from LeNet to ResNet and beyond · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Convolution · filter · feature map · Weight sharing · hierarchy · ResNet · skip connections · transfer learning · filter · CNN architecture · convolution · ResNet · feature map","s":"Image classification — \"what is in this picture?\" — is the foundational vision task, and it's powered by convolution . A convolution slides a small filter (also called a kernel — a tiny grid of weights, say 3×3) across the image; at each position it multiplies the filter by the pixels it covers and sums the result, producing one number."},{"f":"cv3-detection.html","t":"Object detection: finding and boxing objects","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"Not just what, but where — and how many · IoU: measuring box overlap · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Object detection · localization + classification · IoU · one-stage · two-stage · mAP · bounding box · class label · IoU · Object detection","s":"Classification answers \"what is in this image?\" with a single label. But real scenes have multiple objects, and often you need to know where each one is. Object detection does both: for every object in an image, it outputs a bounding box (a rectangle giving the object's location) and a class label with a confidence score. So detection = localization + classification , done for an unknown number of objects at once."},{"f":"cv4-segmentation.html","t":"Segmentation: a label for every pixel","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"A label for every single pixel · The encoder-decoder (U-Net) architecture · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Segmentation · every pixel · Semantic · instance · encoder-decoder (U-Net) · skip connections · IoU/Dice per class · semantic segmentation · instance segmentation · encoder-decoder · U-Net · segmentation","s":"A bounding box (detection) is coarse — it's a rectangle, and rectangles don't capture an object's exact shape. When you need the precise outline, you use segmentation : assigning a class label to every pixel in the image. Instead of \"there's a car in this rectangle,\" segmentation says \"these exact pixels are car, those are road, those are sky.\" It's the finest-grained vision task — a per-pixel classification of the whole image."},{"f":"cv5-vit.html","t":"Vision Transformers: attention for images","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"Treat an image as a sequence of patches · Inductive bias: why CNNs win small, ViTs win big · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Vision Transformer (ViT) · patches · Self-attention gives a global receptive field immediately · Inductive bias · CNNs win on small/medium data; ViTs win at scale · patch embedding · positional embedding · patch embedding · global receptive field · positional embedding · Vision Transformer · inductive bias · transformer · patches","s":"For a decade, convolutional neural networks (CNNs, Track 5 lesson 2) were the way to process images. Then the architecture that revolutionized language — the transformer (Track 6) — was pointed at images, and the Vision Transformer (ViT) was born. The core idea is disarmingly simple. A transformer operates on a sequence of tokens (in language, tokens are word-pieces)."},{"f":"cv6-diffusion.html","t":"Image generation with diffusion","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"Generate by learning to undo noise · Steering it with text, and doing it cheaply in latent space · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · diffusion model · reverse noising · predict the noise · generate · Text conditioning · Latent diffusion (Stable Diffusion) · noise · generative models · latent · reverse process · conditioning · diffusion model · text-to-image · latent diffusion · forward process · autoencoder","s":"Every vision task so far has analyzed an image — labeled it, boxed it, segmented it. Now we flip the problem: generative models create brand-new images that never existed. The technology behind Stable Diffusion, DALL·E, and Midjourney is the diffusion model , and its central idea is beautiful and almost paradoxical: to learn to create images, first learn to destroy them, then run the destruction backward."},{"f":"cv7-multimodal.html","t":"Vision-language & multimodal models","tn":"Computer Vision","k":"5","x":"One shared space for images and text · From matching to describing and answering · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Multimodal · CLIP · shared embedding space · contrastive learning · zero-shot classification · Captioning · VQA · VLMs · CLIP · Multimodal · zero-shot classification · Visual question answering · modality · Image captioning · contrastive learning · vision-language models · embedding space","s":"Until now, vision and language have been separate worlds. Multimodal models join them — a modality is a type of data (images, text, audio), and a multimodal model works across more than one."},{"f":"dl-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Deep Learning","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"What a deep-learning interview round tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Why ReLU? · Why zero_grad()? · Adam vs SGD? · Loss is NaN? · Overfitting fixes? · First debugging step?","s":"Deep-learning interviews probe whether you understand the mechanics — can you explain backprop, diagnose a training failure, justify an architecture? — not just name techniques. The questions below recur constantly; each model answer shows the reasoning an interviewer is listening for, building on the mental map of the whole track."},{"f":"dl1-neuron.html","t":"From a neuron to a network","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"The artificial neuron: a weighted sum, then a squash · Stacking neurons into layers makes a network · Why the nonlinearity is non-negotiable · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · neuron · is · layers · nonlinear activation · layer · bias · activation function · neural network · capacity · weight · hidden layer · output layer · neuron","s":"Deep learning sounds mysterious, but its atom is something you already built in Track 3. A neuron (or \"unit\") takes several inputs, multiplies each by a weight , adds them up, adds a bias , and passes the result through a nonlinear activation function . That weighted sum is exactly a dot product (Lesson 1.3), and a single neuron with a sigmoid activation is logistic regression (Lesson 3.3)."},{"f":"dl2-forward.html","t":"Forward pass & activation functions","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"The forward pass: push data through, layer by layer · The activation functions you'll actually use · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · forward pass · batches · ReLU · Sigmoid/tanh saturate · softmax · sigmoid · linear · saturates · batch · forward pass","s":"The forward pass is how a network turns an input into a prediction. You feed the input to the first layer, which computes a weighted sum, adds a bias, and applies an activation; its output becomes the next layer's input; and so on until the final layer emits the prediction. That's it — a forward pass is just this same three-step move (multiply, add, activate) repeated through the stack."},{"f":"dl3-backprop.html","t":"Backpropagation, step by step","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"The problem: which way should each weight move? · Forward values, then backward gradients · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Backpropagation · forward · backward · autograd · autograd · Backpropagation · computational graph","s":"A fresh network predicts nonsense because its weights are random. To improve, we run gradient descent (Lesson 1.8): nudge each weight a little in the direction that reduces the loss. But that requires knowing, for every single weight , how the loss would change if we wiggled it — its partial derivative L/ w . A real network has millions of weights."},{"f":"dl4-trainloop.html","t":"The training loop, loss & optimizers","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"The loop that turns random weights into a trained model · Optimizers: smarter ways to step downhill · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · training loop · epoch · mini-batches · SGD · momentum · Adam · learning rate · schedule · learning rate · optimizer · SGD · schedule · mini-batches · epoch · Training","s":"You now have all three pieces: a forward pass (compute a prediction), a loss (measure how wrong it is, Lesson 3.4), and backprop (get every gradient). Training is just repeating these in a loop, with one more step — using the gradients to update the weights: repeat each batch zero_grad → forward → loss → backward → step: the heartbeat of every trained net The training loop."},{"f":"dl5-regularization.html","t":"Regularization: dropout, weight decay, batchnorm","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"Deep nets have huge capacity — so they overfit · Dropout: train a different thinned network each step · Weight decay, batch norm, and early stopping · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · regularization · Dropout · Weight decay · Batch norm · Early stopping · redundant · Early stopping · Dropout · Weight decay · inverted dropout · Batch normalization","s":"A network with millions of weights can memorize its training set perfectly, including its noise (the overfitting of Lesson 3.5, now with far more capacity to misbehave). The cure is the same instinct as Track 3.6 — penalize or constrain complexity — but deep learning has its own toolkit for it. We'll cover the four you'll use constantly: dropout, weight decay, batch normalization, and early stopping."},{"f":"dl6-cnn.html","t":"Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"Why images need a different kind of layer · Pooling: shrink while keeping the signal · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · CNNs · filter · parameter sharing · feature map · Pooling · hierarchy · channels · filter · max pooling · pooling · translation-tolerant · Convolutional Neural Network · parameter sharing · convolution · feature map","s":"Imagine feeding a modest 200×200 color image to a plain fully-connected layer. The input has 200×200×3 = 120,000 numbers, so a single hidden layer of 1,000 neurons needs 120 million weights — for one layer. Worse, a fully-connected layer treats every pixel as unrelated, ignoring the obvious fact that nearby pixels form edges and shapes, and that a cat is a cat whether it's in the top-left or bottom-right of the frame."},{"f":"dl7-rnn.html","t":"Sequence models: RNNs, LSTMs, GRUs","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"Data with an order: sequences need memory · The vanishing-gradient problem · LSTMs and GRUs: a gated memory highway · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · RNNs · hidden state · vanishing/exploding gradients · LSTMs/GRUs · cell-state highway · Transformers · GRU · cell state · hidden state · Recurrent Neural Network · gates · LSTM · sequences","s":"CNNs assume grid structure; but language (\"the movie was not good\"), audio, stock prices, and sensor streams are sequences , where order carries meaning and each element depends on what came before. A plain network has no memory — it treats each input independently. A Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) adds memory: it processes a sequence one step at a time, maintaining a hidden state that summarizes everything seen so far and is updated at each step."},{"f":"dl8-dynamics.html","t":"Training dynamics & debugging","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"Most training problems are diagnosable — if you read the signs · Initialization: getting the gradient scale right · A debugging checklist · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · loss curve · Initialization · He · Xavier · overfit a tiny batch · initialization · He · vanish · Xavier · explode","s":"Deep networks fail in a handful of recognizable ways, and an experienced practitioner diagnoses them not by guessing but by reading the evidence . The single most informative instrument is the loss curve : a plot of training and validation loss over epochs. Its shape tells you what's wrong. healthy overfitting LR too high underfitting train = green, validation = red · gap → overfit · both high → underfit · spikes → lower the learning rate Four loss-curve diagnoses."},{"f":"dl9-transfer.html","t":"Transfer learning & fine-tuning","tn":"Deep Learning","k":"4","x":"Don't start from scratch — stand on a pretrained model · Two modes: feature extraction vs fine-tuning · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Transfer learning · backbone · head · Feature extraction · Fine-tuning · Fine-tuning · Transfer learning · head · backbone","s":"Training a strong image or language model from scratch takes millions of examples and days of GPU time — resources most projects don't have. Transfer learning sidesteps this: take a model already trained on a huge dataset, and reuse what it learned for your (smaller) task. A network pretrained on ImageNet has already learned, in its early layers, to detect edges, textures, and shapes — features useful for almost any image task."},{"f":"ev-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Evals & Safety","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"What an evals & safety interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Why is eval hard? · Is 95% accuracy good? · Precision vs recall? · Offline vs online? · A/B pitfalls? · Evaluate generation? · Fairness? · Safety?","s":"Questions about evaluation and safety separate engineers who can build a model from those who can be trusted to deploy one responsibly. Interviewers probe whether you understand that metrics are proxies to be scrutinized, that offline results must be validated online, that generative systems need new evaluation methods, and that fairness, safety, privacy, and accountability are engineering concerns — not someone else's job."},{"f":"ev1-why.html","t":"Why evaluation is the hard part","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"The metric is not the goal · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Evaluation · metric · proxy · Goodhart's law · accuracy paradox · triangulates · Goodhart's law · evaluation","s":"Every track so far has quietly assumed you can tell whether a model is good . This track confronts that assumption head-on, because evaluation — measuring whether a system actually works — is often the hardest and most under-appreciated part of building AI. The core difficulty is that what you can easily measure (a number like accuracy, or click-through rate) is only a proxy for what you actually want (a model that's useful, correct, safe, and fair)."},{"f":"ev2-offline.html","t":"Offline evaluation & datasets","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"Evaluate before you touch real users · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Offline evaluation · train · validation · test · unseen · confusion matrix · precision · recall · test set · training set · Offline evaluation · validation set","s":"Offline evaluation is measuring a model's quality on a fixed dataset, in the lab, before deploying it to real users. It's the workhorse of ML evaluation because it's fast, cheap, and repeatable — you can test a hundred model variants overnight without risking a single real user."},{"f":"ev3-online.html","t":"Online evaluation & A/B testing","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"The only verdict that counts is real users · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Online evaluation · disagree · A/B test · control · treatment · Randomization · statistical significance · statistical significance · A/B test · control · treatment","s":"Offline evaluation (Lesson 12.2) tells you a model looks better on a fixed dataset. Online evaluation tells you whether it actually is better when real users interact with it — and the two often disagree. Online evaluation measures a model's true effect on live traffic, using real user behavior (clicks, purchases, engagement, task success) as the signal."},{"f":"ev4-judge.html","t":"LLM-as-judge","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"How do you grade a million essays? · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Human evaluation · LLM-as-judge · rubric · score and its reasoning · itself a model with biases · validate it against human labels · agreement · rubric · LLM-as-judge","s":"Evaluating generative outputs — the text an LLM writes — is hard because there's no single correct answer to compare against (Lesson 12.1). The gold standard is human evaluation : have people read the outputs and rate them. But humans are slow and expensive, so you can't have them grade the thousands of outputs you'd need to evaluate every model change or monitor a production system."},{"f":"ev5-bias.html","t":"Bias, fairness & toxicity","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"Models learn our biases — and can amplify them · Measuring fairness · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · amplify · Bias enters at every stage · Fairness · demographic parity · equal opportunity · four-fifths rule · disparate impact · detect · disparate impact · demographic parity · Toxicity · fairness · four-fifths rule · proxy features · Bias","s":"An AI model learns patterns from data, and if that data reflects human biases — historical discrimination, skewed representation, prejudiced labels — the model learns those biases too, and can even amplify them. This isn't hypothetical: hiring models have penalized women's résumés, facial recognition has worked far worse for darker skin, and language models reproduce stereotypes present in their training text."},{"f":"ev6-guardrails.html","t":"Guardrails, red-teaming & jailbreaks","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"Safety training isn't enough — you need active defenses · Red-teaming and jailbreaks · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · guardrails · Input filters · output filters · Red-teaming · Jailbreaks · hard to make robust · guardrails · input filter · Red-teaming · output filter · defense in depth · jailbreaks","s":"A deployed AI system, especially one that generates content or takes actions, can be misused or can fail in harmful ways — producing dangerous instructions, toxic content, or leaking private data. Training the model to behave (safety training, RLHF — Track 7) helps, but it's not sufficient, because a model can always be pushed outside its training or tricked."},{"f":"ev7-governance.html","t":"Privacy, security & governance","tn":"Evals & Safety","k":"12","x":"Beyond the model: data, security, and accountability · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · privacy, security, or governance · Privacy · PII · Security · Governance · accountability · design discipline · Privacy · Governance · responsible AI · PII · Security","s":"A model can be accurate, fair, and safe in its outputs and still be irresponsible as a system — if it leaks private data, is vulnerable to attack, or operates with no accountability. This final safety lesson covers the organizational and systemic dimensions of responsible AI : privacy (protecting the data), security (defending the system), and governance (the policies and accountability that hold it all together)."},{"f":"iv1-process.html","t":"How AI/ML interviews are structured (this year)","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"Know the game you're playing · What's different this year · Check yourself · Prepare strategically · funnel · onsite loop · AI-assisted coding · Evaluation is the new system design · GenAI · funnel","s":"Before drilling questions, understand how AI/ML interviews are actually structured — because knowing the stages, what each tests, and what's changed recently lets you prepare deliberately instead of blindly. The process is a funnel : a sequence of increasingly demanding stages that progressively filter candidates, so a strong showing at each stage earns you the next."},{"f":"iv2-fundamentals.html","t":"ML fundamentals","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"The questions that anchor every ML interview · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Bias vs variance? · Overfitting fix? · Precision vs recall? · Generative vs discriminative? · Supervised vs unsupervised? · Why not accuracy on imbalanced data? · L1 vs L2? · What is cross-validation?","s":"ML fundamentals questions test whether you understand why machine learning works, not just which library to call. They recur in nearly every interview because they reveal the depth of your mental model — and interviewers probe with follow-ups, so memorized definitions collapse while genuine understanding holds. This lesson rehearses the classic fundamentals questions with model answers that show the reasoning interviewers want."},{"f":"iv3-dl.html","t":"Deep learning & transformers","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"How modern neural networks actually work · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Backprop? · Vanishing gradients? · CNN vs RNN? · Self-attention? · Why transformers > RNNs? · Dropout? · Embeddings? · Why deep (many layers)?","s":"Deep learning questions test whether you understand the machinery behind modern AI — how networks learn (backpropagation), why they sometimes don't (vanishing gradients), which architecture fits which data, and above all the transformer and attention that power today's LLMs. As with fundamentals, interviewers probe the why , so intuition beats memorization."},{"f":"iv4-llm.html","t":"LLM / GenAI & RAG","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"The questions that dominate current interviews · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · How are LLMs trained? · RAG vs fine-tuning? · Why hallucination? · Temperature? · Chain-of-thought? · Few-shot / in-context learning? · Agent? · Context window?","s":"LLM, GenAI, and RAG questions are now standard across most ML interviews, because these systems are what teams are building. They test whether you understand how large language models are trained and used, and how to build reliable applications on top of them — prompting, retrieval, agents, and evaluation. As the whole field has shifted here, so have interviews."},{"f":"iv5-systemdesign.html","t":"ML system design","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"The round that most separates candidates · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · First move? · Recommender/search? · Recurring pattern? · RAG assistant? · Scale a service? · Latency SLA? · 2026 emphasis? · Best design principle?","s":"ML system design is often the most decisive interview round, because it can't be crammed — it tests whether you can take a vague, open-ended problem and drive it to a coherent, justified design while reasoning about scale, cost, and trade-offs out loud. There's no single right answer; the interviewer evaluates how you think ."},{"f":"iv6-coding.html","t":"Coding & implementation","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"The coding round, old and new · Check yourself · Mock interview prompts · and · Communicate out loud · understand · AI-assisted coding rounds · both modes · ML-specific coding","s":"The coding round tests whether you can actually implement, not just discuss. It spans two flavors: general problem-solving (data structures and algorithms) and ML-specific coding — implementing algorithms or metrics from scratch (k-means, k-nearest-neighbors, gradient descent, precision/recall, cosine similarity), or writing practical data/model code."},{"f":"iv7-behavioral.html","t":"Behavioral & project deep-dives","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"13","x":"Teams hire people, not just skills · Check yourself · Prepare your stories · STAR · STAR stories · project deep-dive · failure · own it · conflict","s":"Behavioral rounds and project deep-dives are where technically strong candidates most often stumble — precisely because they under-prepare, treating these as an afterthought to the \"real\" technical rounds. That's a mistake: interviewers use these rounds to answer questions your coding can't — Would I want to work with this person?"},{"f":"llm-interview.html","t":"Interview check: LLMs & GenAI","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"What an LLM / GenAI interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Base vs chat model? · Why hallucination? · In-context learning? · Chain-of-thought? · Chinchilla? · DPO vs RLHF?","s":"LLM interviews probe whether you understand how these systems are built and used end to end: the training pipeline, the practical levers (decoding, prompting, fine-tuning), and the trade-offs. The questions below are the ones that come up constantly; each model answer shows the reasoning interviewers want to hear. next-token prediction, scaled and aligned, became the assistants and image generators you use The Track 7 mental model."},{"f":"llm1-what.html","t":"What is a large language model","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"A large language model is a transformer, scaled up · The life of an LLM: pretrain, fine-tune, align, deploy · What scale buys — and what it doesn't · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · LLM · parameters · compute · lifecycle · in-context learning · hallucination · next-token prediction · large language model · supervised fine-tuning · alignment · deployment · parameters · in-context learning · hallucinate · compute · pretraining · data","s":"You already built the architecture of an LLM in Track 6: a stack of transformer decoder blocks trained to predict the next token (Lesson 6.3). A large language model (LLM) is exactly that — there's no new architecture — but scaled to an extreme along three axes at once: billions of parameters (weights), trillions of tokens of training data , and enormous compute (thousands of GPUs for months)."},{"f":"llm2-pretrain-finetune.html","t":"Pretraining vs fine-tuning","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"Two training stages: build knowledge, then specialize · Fine-tune, retrieve, or just prompt? · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Pretraining · Fine-tuning · SFT / instruction tuning · transfer learning · prompt · retrieve · fine-tune · supervised fine-tuning · instruction tuning · Fine-tuning · Pretraining","s":"An LLM is created in two distinct training phases, and they could not be more different in scale and purpose. This is exactly the transfer-learning idea from Lesson 4.9 — pretrain a general model once, then adapt it cheaply — applied at massive scale. next-token Stage 2: FINE-TUNE (supervised) small labeled task data specialized model pretraining (once, expensive) gives general ability; fine-tuning (cheap) adapts it to a task or style Pretrain, then fine-tune."},{"f":"llm3-alignment.html","t":"Instruction tuning & RLHF/DPO","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"From \"follows instructions\" to \"helpful, honest, harmless\" · RLHF: learning from human preferences · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Alignment · RLHF · reward model · DPO · logistic regression on preferences · preference data · RLHF · Alignment · DPO · Bradley-Terry · reward model · PPO","s":"Supervised fine-tuning (Lesson 7.2) teaches a model to follow instructions, but it doesn't fully capture the nuances of what makes a response good: helpful but not sycophantic, honest about uncertainty, harmless when asked to do something dangerous. These qualities are hard to specify with a fixed dataset of \"correct\" answers — there's no single right response, and it's easier for humans to compare two responses than to write the ideal one from scratch."},{"f":"llm4-decoding.html","t":"Decoding strategies","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"The model gives a distribution; decoding chooses the token · Sampling: temperature, top-k, top-p · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · decoding · Greedy · beam search · Sampling · Temperature · top-k · top-p · Decoding · Beam search · greedy · sampling","s":"At every step, a language model outputs a probability distribution over the next token (Lesson 6.3). But to actually generate text it must commit to one token. Decoding is the strategy for picking that token from the distribution — and it matters enormously: the same model with different decoding settings can produce dull repetition, incoherent randomness, or fluent creative text."},{"f":"llm5-prompting.html","t":"Prompting techniques","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"Same model, better answers — just by asking well · The anatomy of a good prompt · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Prompting · Zero-shot · few-shot · Chain-of-thought · system / instruction / examples / input / output format · string assembly · Prompting · examples · Few-shot · in-context learning · output format · chain-of-thought · zero-shot · input · instruction · system message","s":"A trained LLM is fixed, but how you ask it dramatically changes what you get back. Prompting is the craft of writing the input so the model produces the response you want — and it's the highest-leverage, zero-cost way to use an LLM (no training, instant). The simplest is zero-shot : just state the task (\"Translate this to French: ...\")."},{"f":"llm6-peft.html","t":"Parameter-efficient fine-tuning (LoRA/QLoRA)","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"Fine-tuning a giant model without paying for all of it · QLoRA: fine-tune a huge model on one GPU · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · PEFT · LoRA · low-rank · no catastrophic forgetting · QLoRA · LoRA · QLoRA · low-rank · quantizing","s":"Fine-tuning (Lesson 7.2) means updating a model's weights — but for a model with billions of parameters, updating all of them is expensive. You need memory not just for the weights, but also for their gradients and the optimizer's state (Adam keeps two extra numbers per weight, Lesson 4.4), which together can triple or quadruple the memory."},{"f":"llm7-scaling.html","t":"Scaling laws & emergent behavior","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"Performance you can forecast: scaling laws · Emergence: abilities that switch on with scale · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Scaling laws · power law · forecastable · Chinchilla · Emergence · diminish · floor · Chinchilla · scaling laws · power law · emergence","s":"One of the most consequential discoveries about LLMs is that their performance is predictable . As you scale up compute, data, and parameters, the model's loss falls in a smooth, regular way — a power law . Plot loss against compute on log-log axes and you get a remarkably straight line: every multiplication of compute buys a fixed reduction in loss."},{"f":"llm8-diffusion.html","t":"Diffusion models & image generation","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"Making images by removing noise · The training objective: predict the noise · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Diffusion models · reverse · Forward · Reverse · predict the noise · Text conditioning · latent diffusion · reverse process · conditioned · diffusion model · latent diffusion · forward process","s":"Transformers generate text by predicting the next token. Image generation works completely differently, and the dominant approach is the diffusion model — the technology behind Stable Diffusion, DALL·E, and Midjourney. The core idea is almost paradoxical: teach a model to turn noise into images by first teaching it to turn images into noise, then running that backward."},{"f":"llm9-othergen.html","t":"VAEs & GANs in context","tn":"LLMs & GenAI","k":"7","x":"A map of how machines generate · VAEs: a smooth latent space · GANs: a forger and a detective · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · sample · Autoregressive · Diffusion · VAE · GAN · mode collapse · reparameterization trick · Generative Adversarial Network · latent · encoder · discriminator · decoder · reparameterization trick · generator · autoregressive · Variational Autoencoder","s":"Diffusion (Lesson 7.8) is one way to generate data, but it's worth seeing the whole family, because each approach makes different trade-offs and you'll meet them all. Every generative model has the same goal — learn a data distribution well enough to sample new examples from it — but they get there differently."},{"f":"m-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Math Foundations","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"What the math round actually tests · Rapid-fire conceptual questions · Whiteboard derivations · Explain it to a non-expert · Spot the trap · Why first. · Think out loud. · Connect the pieces. · Respect uncertainty. · Make it concrete.","s":"Interviewers rarely ask you to grind through arithmetic. They probe whether the foundations are load-bearing : can you explain why a method works, derive a gradient on a whiteboard, and translate math into plain English for a non-technical stakeholder? This checkpoint rehearses exactly those moves across everything in Track 1. Treat each question as a mini-performance: say the why first, then the mechanics."},{"f":"m1-vectors.html","t":"Vectors: the language of data","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"Why we have to turn things into numbers · The second way to see a vector: an arrow · How long is a vector? The norm · The only two things we ever do to vectors · Move 1 — Addition (combine two vectors) · Move 2 — Scaling (stretch, shrink, or flip one vector) · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · vector · feature · dimension · list of numbers · arrow · norm · element-wise addition · scaling · variables · Pythagorean theorem · library · scalar · origin · notation · real numbers · numbe","s":"You do not need to be \"good at math\" to do this. We will build every idea from the ground up, define every word the first time it appears, and never assume you remember a formula from school. If a sentence ever uses a term you don't know, that's a bug in the lesson — every term gets explained. Take it slowly; re-read anything twice."},{"f":"m10-statistics.html","t":"Statistics for ML: expectation, variance, MLE & the normal","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"From \"what could happen\" to \"what the data says\" · Variance and standard deviation: how spread out · Sampling: why a test set tells the truth · Maximum likelihood: where loss functions come from · The normal distribution and the Central Limit Theorem · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Expectation · Variance · standard deviation · sample mean · Maximum likelihood · Central Limit Theorem · Law of Large Numbers · Bessel's correction · maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) · cross-entro","s":"Probability (Lesson 1.9) reasons forward: given a model, what outcomes are likely? Statistics reasons backward: given a finite, noisy pile of data, what can we conclude? That backward direction is the everyday job of an ML engineer — estimate a quantity, judge how much to trust it, and pick the model that the data supports. Two simple summaries do most of the work: the center of a bunch of numbers and how spread out they are."},{"f":"m2-matrices.html","t":"Matrices & matrix multiplication","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"From one vector to a whole grid · Matrix × vector: the move at the center of ML · Matrix × matrix: many recipes at once · The payoff: this is a neural-network layer · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · matrix · shape · Matrix × vector · Matrix × matrix · Shape rule · shape · identity · row · linear · layer · column · bias · dot product · entry · activation function · nonlinearity · matrix","s":"In Lesson 1.1 one thing (a house) became one vector (a list of numbers). But you never have just one house — you have a spreadsheet full of them. If you stack many vectors on top of each other, you get a grid of numbers, and a grid of numbers is called a matrix (plural: matrices). That's the whole idea: a matrix is just a rectangle of numbers arranged in rows and columns."},{"f":"m3-dot-product.html","t":"Dot products, similarity & projection","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"The question behind half of modern AI · The computation: multiply pairs, then add · What the number means: alignment · Cosine similarity: compare direction, ignore size · Projection: how much of one vector lies along another · The payoff: this is how attention works · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · dot product · alignment · zero = right angle (orthogonal) · Cosine similarity · Projection · Attention · cosine · projection · orthogonal · sum · query · unit vector · angle · attenti","s":"\"Here's a song you liked — find more like it.\" \"Here's a search box — find the most relevant pages.\" \"Here's a word — which earlier words should I pay attention to?\" Recommendations, search, and the attention mechanism inside every modern language model are all answering one question: how similar are these two vectors? To answer it, a machine needs to turn the fuzzy idea of \"similar\" into a single number it can compare and rank."},{"f":"m4-linear-systems.html","t":"Linear systems, span, rank & the inverse","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"Turning the question around · Span: everywhere your vectors can reach · Linear independence: does each vector add something new? · Rank: the true number of dimensions · The inverse — and when it doesn't exist · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · linear system · one · none · infinitely many · Span · independent · Rank · invertible · linear equation · parallel · solve · least-squares · satisfy · full rank · rank · equation · rank-deficient · system · span · linear system","s":"In Lesson 1.2 we always knew the matrix A and the input x , and we computed the output b = Ax . Now we flip it: we know the output b and want to find the input x . This is called solving a linear system , and it's the quiet workhorse beneath linear regression, \"best-fit\" lines, and the basic question \"can my model even represent this data?\" Let's define the words."},{"f":"m5-eigen-pca.html","t":"Eigenvectors, eigenvalues & a first look at PCA","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"The directions a matrix refuses to rotate · Data has directions of more and less spread · PCA: rotate onto those axes, then drop the boring ones · How many components to keep? Read the scree plot · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · eigenvector · eigenvalue · covariance matrix · principal components · PCA · explained variance ratio · scree plot · transformation · eigenvectors · mean · scree plot · dimensionality reduction · Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) · variance · principal c","s":"In Lesson 1.2 you learned that a matrix is a transformation — multiply vectors by it and it moves them around, generally rotating them (turning their direction) and stretching them (changing their length). But for almost every matrix there are a few special directions it only stretches, never rotates : a vector pointing that way comes out pointing the exact same way, just longer or shorter."},{"f":"m6-derivatives.html","t":"Derivatives & gradients: slope as a signal to improve","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"The one question a model asks over and over · Zoom in far enough and everything looks like a straight line · Many knobs at once: partial derivatives and the gradient · The gradient points uphill — so step the other way · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · derivative · partial derivative · gradient · steepest increase · Autograd · function · gradient · derivative · contour map · chain rule · parameters · rate of change · power rule · automatic differentiation · slope · partial deriva","s":"Everything so far has been about representing data. Now we start improving a model, and \"improving\" comes down to one question the model asks millions of times during training: \"If I nudge this number a little, does my error get bigger or smaller — and by how much?\" Answer that for every adjustable number, and you know exactly how to make the model better."},{"f":"m7-chain-rule.html","t":"The chain rule","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"Why one little rule rules all of deep learning · The chain rule: multiply the local slopes · Computational graphs and backpropagation · Run it Try the code yourself · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · composition · chain rule · computational graph · Backpropagation · product of local derivatives · composition · chain rule · backpropagation · forward pass · backward pass · computational graph","s":"A neural network is a tall stack of steps: the input goes into step 1, its output feeds step 2, that feeds step 3, and so on, until the last step produces a prediction and an error. In math, a stack like this is called a composition — functions inside functions , written f(g(x)) (read \"f of g of x\": first do g to x , then do f to the result)."},{"f":"m8-gradient-descent.html","t":"Gradient descent: how models actually learn","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"Learning, at last: make the error as small as possible · The update rule · The learning rate is the dial that makes or breaks training · How much data per step? Batch, stochastic, mini-batch · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · minimizing a loss function · Gradient descent · learning rate · Mini-batch · learning rate · minimizing · parameters · loss function · gradient descent · hyperparameter · plateau · local minimum · non-convex · convex","s":"This is the lesson where everything so far becomes \"learning.\" Training a model means choosing its numbers (its parameters ) so its predictions are as close to the truth as possible. We measure \"how wrong it is right now\" with a loss function L — a single number that is large when the model is bad and small when it's good."},{"f":"m9-probability.html","t":"Probability essentials: uncertainty, distributions, Bayes","tn":"Math Foundations","k":"1","x":"Why models speak in probabilities · Random variables and distributions · Conditional probability and Bayes' rule · Why classifiers output probabilities, not labels · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Probability · distribution · Bernoulli · categorical · Gaussian · Bayes' rule · probabilities · outcome · mean · likelihood · log-probabilities · sample space · prior · independent · maximum likelihood estimation · Bayes' rule · standard deviation · conditional · posterior","s":"The real world is noisy and the future is uncertain, so a good model rarely says \"this email is spam.\" It says \"this email is spam with probability 0.92.\" That hedge is a feature, not a weakness: it lets you set sensible cut-offs, weigh risks, and combine evidence."},{"f":"nlp-interview.html","t":"Interview check: NLP & Transformers","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"What an NLP / transformers interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Attention formula? · Q, K, V? · Why positional encoding? · Attention complexity? · Subword tokenization? · Causal mask?","s":"Transformer interviews probe whether you understand attention from the inside — can you walk through the math, justify the design choices, and pick the right architecture? These questions come up in nearly every modern ML interview, because transformers underpin everything. Each model answer below shows the reasoning interviewers listen for."},{"f":"nlp1-tokenization.html","t":"Text to numbers: tokenization","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"Turning text into numbers a model can read · How big should a token be? Characters, words, subwords · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Tokenization · tokens · ID · subwords · Subword · learned · special tokens · tokenization · subword · Byte-Pair Encoding · tokens · WordPiece · special tokens · vocabulary · ID · out-of-vocabulary","s":"A neural network does arithmetic on numbers (Track 4), but language is text. The first step of every NLP system is tokenization : splitting text into small pieces called tokens , then mapping each token to an integer ID via a lookup table called the vocabulary . The model never sees letters — only these IDs, which it will turn into vectors (embeddings) in the next lesson."},{"f":"nlp2-embeddings.html","t":"Word embeddings","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"From meaningless IDs to vectors that carry meaning · Directions encode relationships · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · embedding · meaning becomes geometry · cosine similarity · directions · word2vec / GloVe · embedding · GloVe · cosine similarity · word2vec · embedding table","s":"Tokenization gave us integer IDs, but an ID like 2543 is an arbitrary label — there's nothing about the number 2543 that says \"cat,\" and \"cat\" (2543) is no closer to \"kitten\" (8001) than to \"tractor\" (4112). We need a representation where similar words are actually close . That representation is the embedding : a learned dense vector (a list of, say, 768 numbers) assigned to each token."},{"f":"nlp3-lm.html","t":"Language modeling basics","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"One objective to rule them all: predict the next token · From counting to neural networks · Generation = predict, append, repeat · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · language model · probability distribution · self-supervised · n-gram · neural · Perplexity · Generation · autoregressive · perplexity · language model · n-grams · Neural language models · context · autoregressive · self-supervised","s":"A language model does one deceptively simple thing: given some text so far (the context ), it predicts what comes next. More precisely, it outputs a probability distribution over the entire vocabulary — how likely each possible next token is."},{"f":"nlp4-attention.html","t":"Attention, intuitively","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"The problem: which earlier words matter for this one? · Query, Key, Value: attention as soft lookup · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Attention · one step · parallel · Query · Key · Value · softmax · soft, differentiable · Value · Query · Key · Attention","s":"Consider \"the cat sat down because it was tired.\" To represent \"it\" correctly, the model must realize \"it\" refers to \"cat,\" not \"down.\" More generally, the meaning of every word depends on specific other words in the sentence, often far away. RNNs (Lesson 4.7) tried to carry this context in a single hidden state passed step by step, but that state is a bottleneck and forgets distant words."},{"f":"nlp5-selfattention.html","t":"Self-attention & multi-head attention","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"Self-attention: every token attends to every token · The attention matrix · Multi-head attention: several at once · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Self-attention · scaling · attention matrix · Multi-head · Self-attention · Multi-head attention · scaling · attention matrix","s":"Self-attention applies the attention from Lesson 6.4 within a single sequence: every token is a Query and a Key and a Value, so each token attends to every token (itself included) and rebuilds its representation as a blend of the whole sentence, weighted by relevance. \"Self\" because the queries, keys, and values all come from the same sequence."},{"f":"nlp6-transformer.html","t":"The Transformer architecture","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"The transformer block: attention + feed-forward, wrapped well · Stacking blocks into the full model · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · transformer block · residual + layer norm · Attention · FFN · Residuals · layer norm · same shape · residual connections · layer normalization · transformer block · feed-forward network","s":"Self-attention mixes information across tokens, but on its own it's all linear blending. The transformer block combines it with a per-token feed-forward network (a small MLP, Lesson 4.2) that adds nonlinear processing, and wraps both in the two stabilizing tricks from Track 4: residual connections and layer normalization . That's the entire unit — and a transformer is just a stack of these identical blocks."},{"f":"nlp7-positional.html","t":"Positional encoding","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"Attention is order-blind, so we must add position · How to build the position vectors · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · order-blind · Positional encoding · Sinusoidal · learned · rotary (RoPE) · RoPE · positional encoding · rotary · sinusoidal · learned","s":"Self-attention has a surprising blind spot: it treats its input as a set , not a sequence. If you shuffle the token order, attention computes the same relationships — just reordered. So on its own, a transformer can't tell \"dog bites man\" from \"man bites dog,\" even though word order flips the meaning. We have to explicitly tell the model where each token sits, and we do it with positional encoding ."},{"f":"nlp8-architectures.html","t":"Encoder/decoder vs decoder-only","tn":"NLP & Transformers","k":"6","x":"Same block, three shapes for three jobs · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Encoder-only · bidirectional · Decoder-only · causal · Encoder–decoder · cross-attention · causal mask · Decoder-only · causal · GPT · T5 · Encoder–decoder · bidirectional · BERT · Encoder-only · cross-attending","s":"The transformer block (Lesson 6.6) is a universal building unit, but how you arrange the blocks — and crucially, what each token is allowed to attend to — gives three architectures suited to different tasks. Encoder-only models (like BERT ) use bidirectional attention: every token attends to every other token, both left and right."},{"f":"ops-interview.html","t":"Interview check: MLOps","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"What an MLOps interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · What is MLOps? · Train/serve skew? · Data vs concept drift? · Why a model registry? · Online vs batch serving? · Scaling levers? · Two monitoring layers? · Reproducibility needs?","s":"MLOps questions separate people who can train a model from people who can run one. Interviewers probe whether you understand that deploying a model is the start of the hard part, not the end — whether you grasp the lifecycle loop, can reason about serving and scaling trade-offs, and know why models decay and how to keep them healthy."},{"f":"ops1-lifecycle.html","t":"The ML lifecycle","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"A model is the easy part; running it is the job · The lifecycle is a loop, not a line · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · MLOps · production · ML lifecycle · lifecycle · production · MLOps","s":"Every track so far has been about building models — training them, evaluating them, prompting them. This track is about everything that happens around the model to make it actually useful in the real world."},{"f":"ops2-tracking.html","t":"Experiment tracking & reproducibility","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"If you didn't log it, it didn't happen · Reproducibility: getting the same result twice · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Experiment tracking · parameters · metrics · artifacts · Reproducibility · seed · parameters · artifacts · metrics · Experiment tracking · reproducibility · experiments","s":"Training a model is not a single act — it's dozens or hundreds of experiments : you try a learning rate of 0.1, then 0.01; two layers, then four; this feature set, then that one. Each run produces a model with some score. The problem is memory: after thirty runs, which settings gave the best result? What data did the good run use?"},{"f":"ops3-pipelines.html","t":"Data & feature pipelines, feature stores","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"Models are only as good as the data plumbing · Train/serve skew: the silent killer · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · data/feature pipeline · features · Train/serve skew · one place · feature store · offline · online · features · train/serve skew · data pipeline · feature store","s":"A model doesn't eat raw data — it eats features : the processed numerical inputs computed from raw data (Lesson 2.x). \"Raw data\" might be a database row like amount: 100, day: \"Sat\" ; a feature is something the model can use, like amount_log = 4.6 or is_weekend = True ."},{"f":"ops4-registry.html","t":"Model registry & versioning","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"Which model is live right now? · Promotion and rollback · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · model registry · version · stage · Promotion · Rollback · archived, not deleted · model registry · stage · Promotion · Rollback · version","s":"Once you're training models regularly (Lesson 10.2), you accumulate many of them — v1, v2, v3, last Tuesday's experiment, the one with the new features. Now urgent questions appear: which model is currently serving production traffic? Which was live last month when that incident happened? If the new model misbehaves, how do we instantly go back to the old one?"},{"f":"ops5-serving.html","t":"Packaging & serving","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"From a saved model to a service users can call · Three ways to serve: online, batch, streaming · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Packaging · container · Serving · Online · latency · Batch · throughput · Streaming · Streaming serving · Online serving · packaging · endpoint · Batch serving · latency · throughput · serving · container · serve","s":"A trained model is a file — a blob of learned weights sitting on disk. That file can't do anything by itself; to be useful it has to serve predictions: receive an input, run the model, and return an output, on demand. Getting from \"file on disk\" to \"service users can call\" involves two steps. First, packaging : bundling the model file together with everything it needs to run — the inference code, and the software dependencies (the exact libraries and versions)."},{"f":"ops6-scaling.html","t":"Scaling inference","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"One server can't serve a million users · Making each prediction cheaper · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Horizontal scaling · replicas · load balancer · Autoscaling · batching · caching · quantization/compression · hardware · replicas · autoscaling · load balancer · hardware · batching · caching · quantization · Scaling inference · horizontal scaling","s":"A single packaged model behind a single server (Lesson 10.5) works fine in a demo. But real traffic — thousands or millions of requests, with spikes at peak hours — will overwhelm one server: requests queue up, latency balloons, and eventually it falls over. Scaling inference is the practice of serving predictions reliably and affordably under heavy, variable load."},{"f":"ops7-monitoring.html","t":"Monitoring & observability","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"A deployed model can fail silently · The hard part: measuring quality without labels · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · silently · monitoring · Operational monitoring · Model monitoring · labels · proxy signals · monitoring · observability · model monitoring · proxy signals · operational monitoring","s":"Ordinary software fails loudly: it crashes, throws an error, returns a 500. An ML model has a scarier failure mode — it keeps running, returns plausible-looking predictions, and is quietly wrong . Accuracy can erode for months with no error message, no crash, nothing in the logs, while the model makes worse and worse decisions and nobody notices until the business impact shows up."},{"f":"ops8-drift.html","t":"Data & model drift, retraining","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"Why models go stale: the world moves · Retraining: closing the loop · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Drift · Data drift · Concept drift · without labels · Retraining · Data drift · Retraining · drift · Concept drift","s":"A model is trained on a snapshot of the world — the data as it was during training. It learns the patterns in that data. But the world doesn't hold still: customer behavior shifts, prices change, new products appear, fashions turn, fraudsters invent new tricks. As reality drifts away from the training snapshot, the model's learned patterns become increasingly outdated, and its accuracy quietly decays."},{"f":"ops9-cicd.html","t":"CI/CD for ML","tn":"MLOps & Serving","k":"10","x":"Automating the path from change to production · The deployment gate: tests and model quality · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · CI/CD · CI · CD · pipeline · CT · gate · baseline · unit tests · gate · CI · CI/CD · CT · CD · pipeline","s":"By now the lifecycle loop has many moving parts — train, test, validate, package, deploy, monitor. Doing these by hand is slow and error-prone: someone forgets to run the tests, deploys the wrong version, or skips validation under deadline pressure. CI/CD is the practice of automating this path."},{"f":"py-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Python & Data","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"What the Python & data round tests · Rapid-fire conceptual questions · Coding challenges (say your reasoning aloud) · Spot the trap · Reach for vectorization first. · Debug shapes out loud. · Name the rule, not just the fix. · Be leak-paranoid. · Check before you trust.","s":"Data and Python interviews test fluency under mild pressure : can you vectorize a loop on the spot, read a shape error and fix it, write a groupby without hesitating, and spot a data leak in a pipeline someone describes? These are the daily motions of the job, so interviewers want to see them as reflexes, not puzzles. This checkpoint rehearses exactly those moves."},{"f":"py1-stack.html","t":"Why Python, and the scientific stack","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"Why Python, and what \"the stack\" means · The workflow is a loop, not a straight line · Notebooks vs. scripts, and keeping work reproducible · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · scientific stack · NumPy · pandas · Matplotlib · scikit-learn · PyTorch/TensorFlow · loop · Notebooks · list · dependencies · notebook · scientific stack · array · vectorization · random seed · library · import · script · Python","s":"This track is about the everyday tools . You don't need prior coding experience — we'll define every term, including the plain programming words. If you've never written Python, that's fine: read the code as \"recipes,\" and the companion notebooks let you run each one and watch what happens. Going slowly here pays off for the rest of the course."},{"f":"py2-numpy.html","t":"NumPy arrays & vectorization","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"The array: one data structure under all of ML · Vectorization: operate on whole arrays, not one element at a time · Indexing, slicing, and boolean masks · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · array · shape · dtype · axes · Vectorize · Slice · mask · read and write · array · vectorization · Slicing · view · loop · index · boolean mask · element-wise","s":"Every dataset, image, sound clip, and neural-network tensor is, underneath, a NumPy array (its full name is ndarray , for \"n-dimensional array\"). An array is just a grid of numbers, all of the same type. Three properties describe any array, and you'll reach for them constantly: axis 0 (rows) axis 1 (columns) shape = (3, 4) dtype = int64 12 numbers, one contiguous block Anatomy of a 2-D array."},{"f":"py3-broadcasting.html","t":"Broadcasting & array operations","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"Combining different shapes without writing loops · The two rules · Axes in reductions: which dimension you collapse · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Broadcasting · from the right · equal · 1 · missing · the axis you name disappears · reductions · broadcasting","s":"Constantly in ML you need to combine arrays whose shapes don't match: add the same bias to every row of a batch, subtract each column's average from all the rows, scale features. The clumsy way is a loop. NumPy's elegant way is broadcasting — it automatically \"stretches\" the smaller array across the larger one so the operation applies element-wise, without ever copying data ."},{"f":"py4-pandas.html","t":"pandas: Series & DataFrames","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"Real data is a labeled table · Selecting and filtering · groupby: split, apply, combine · merge: joining tables on a key · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Series · DataFrame · index · groupby · merge · key · split–apply–combine · Series · DataFrame · merge · key · CSV · pandas · index","s":"NumPy arrays are perfect for pure numbers, but real data almost never arrives as a clean grid. It comes as labeled tables : columns with names like \"customer\" and \"amount,\" rows identified by a label, and a mix of numbers, text, and dates — the kind of thing you'd open in a spreadsheet or a CSV file (a CSV , \"comma-separated values,\" is the most common plain-text table format)."},{"f":"py5-cleaning.html","t":"Data cleaning & preparation","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"Garbage in, garbage out · Missing values · Encoding categories into numbers · Scaling numeric features · The split, and the leakage that ruins everything · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · missing values · encode · scale · One-hot · Standardize · Data leakage · training set only · Pipeline · Scaling · Data cleaning and preparation · one-hot encoding · test set · data leakage · Pipeline · impute · ordinal","s":"A model is only as good as the data you feed it, and raw data is almost never ready to use: it has missing entries, values stored as the wrong type, text categories a model can't read, and numbers on wildly different scales. Data cleaning and preparation is the work of turning that mess into a clean table of numbers a model can learn from."},{"f":"py6-plotting.html","t":"Plotting with Matplotlib","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"You can't understand data you can't see · The Figure / Axes object model · Which chart for which question? · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Figure · Axes · histogram · scatter · line · bar · histogram · Figure · Axes · Plotting · distribution · Matplotlib","s":"A table of summary numbers can hide a lot: two datasets can share the exact same average and still look completely different. A single picture reveals a lopsided distribution, a stray outlier, a broken sensor, or a data leak in seconds — things a wall of numbers conceals. Plotting (drawing charts of your data) is the fastest exploration and debugging tool you have, and it's how you communicate findings to people who don't read code."},{"f":"py7-eda.html","t":"Putting it together: an EDA workflow","tn":"Python for ML","k":"2","x":"Look before you model · The checklist, step by step · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · EDA · Always look at raw rows · Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) · outlier · correlation","s":"Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is the disciplined first look at a dataset, before any modeling. Its purpose is to understand the data and find problems while they're still cheap to fix — wrong types, missing values, outliers, duplicates, suspicious relationships, and leaks."},{"f":"rag-interview.html","t":"Interview check: RAG","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"What a RAG interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · Why RAG over fine-tuning for facts? · Most common RAG failure? · Bi- vs cross-encoder? · Why ANN over brute force? · Same embedding model for docs and queries? · Reduce hallucination?","s":"RAG questions are staples of modern ML interviews because RAG is the most-deployed LLM technique. Interviewers probe whether you understand the full pipeline, can debug it (most failures are retrieval failures), and know how to evaluate it. The model answers below show the reasoning interviewers want. retrieve relevant chunks, put them in the prompt, generate a grounded &amp; cited answer — then measure it The Track 8 mental model."},{"f":"rag1-why.html","t":"Why RAG exists","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"The problem RAG solves · RAG vs fine-tuning vs long context · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · frozen knowledge · hallucinate · private data · RAG · current · grounded · private-aware · fine-tuning · private data · frozen · hallucinates · Retrieval-Augmented Generation","s":"Track 7 ended on three hard limits of even the best LLM. Its knowledge is frozen at training time — it can't know today's news or anything after its cutoff. It hallucinates — confidently inventing plausible-sounding falsehoods. And it has never seen your private data — your company's documents, your codebase, your customer records."},{"f":"rag2-chunking.html","t":"Chunking strategies","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"Why you can't retrieve whole documents · Overlap, structure, and metadata · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Chunking · Chunk size · Overlap · Recursive · semantic · metadata · Structure-aware splitting · Semantic · chunk size · chunking · metadata · Fixed-size · Overlap · Recursive","s":"RAG retrieves text to put in the prompt, but you can't retrieve and embed an entire 100-page document as one unit. First, it wouldn't fit in the prompt. Second — and more subtly — a single embedding (Lesson 6.2) for a huge document would be a blurry average of everything it covers, so it wouldn't match any specific question well."},{"f":"rag3-embeddings.html","t":"Embeddings for retrieval","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"Retrieval = nearest neighbors in embedding space · Embedding models and the details that matter · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Retrieval · nearest neighbors · cosine similarity · Embeddings beat keywords · embedding model · normalize · dimension · cosine similarity · embedding · nearest neighbors · embedding model","s":"To retrieve the chunks relevant to a question, we need to compare meaning, not match words. The tool is the embedding from Lesson 6.2: a learned vector where similar meanings have similar vectors. The recipe is exactly the semantic search teased in Lesson 6.2's practice. Offline: embed every chunk and store its vector. At query time: embed the question, then find the chunk vectors closest to the query vector — the nearest neighbors — and return them."},{"f":"rag4-vectordb.html","t":"Vector databases & ANN search","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"Finding nearest neighbors fast, at scale · How ANN indexes work: HNSW and IVF · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Brute-force · ANN · recall · HNSW · IVF · vector database · brute-force · approximate nearest neighbor · IVF · recall · HNSW · index · vector database","s":"Retrieval means finding the chunk vectors closest to a query vector (Lesson 8.3). The obvious way — brute-force search — compares the query to every stored vector and keeps the closest. That's exact and simple, but it's O(N) : with 10 million chunks, every single query computes 10 million similarities, which is far too slow for a real application answering many queries per second."},{"f":"rag5-rerank.html","t":"Retrieval, reranking & hybrid search","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"The closest vector isn't always the best chunk · Reranking: retrieve wide, then judge precisely · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · bi-encoder · Hybrid search · Reranking · cross-encoder · Query rewriting · cross-encoder · query rewriting · bi-encoder · hybrid search · BM25 · reranking","s":"Embedding retrieval (Lesson 8.3) is fast because it embeds the query and each chunk independently — a bi-encoder — and compares vectors. But that independence is also its weakness: the model never looks at the query and a specific chunk together , so it can only judge relevance through a single similarity number. A chunk can be topically close yet not actually answer the question, or the true best chunk can rank slightly below a more generic one."},{"f":"rag6-pipeline.html","t":"Building a RAG pipeline","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"Two phases: index offline, query online · Assembling the prompt — and the budget · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · RAG pipeline · indexing · querying · Prompt assembly · cite · abstain · token budget · prompt assembly · indexing · token budget · querying · RAG pipeline","s":"You now have every ingredient — chunking (7.2), embeddings (7.3), vector search (7.4), reranking (7.5). A RAG pipeline assembles them into a working system with two distinct phases that run at different times. QUERYING (online, per request) query embed retrieve + rerank prompt = query + chunks LLM → answer + citations search A full RAG pipeline."},{"f":"rag7-eval.html","t":"Evaluating RAG","tn":"RAG & Vector Search","k":"8","x":"RAG can fail in two places — so measure both · Evaluating the generated answer: the RAG triad · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · retrieval · generation · Recall@k · Precision@k · MRR · recall@k · RAG triad · faithfulness · MRR · nDCG · LLM-as-judge · Precision@k · Context relevance · Recall@k · Answer relevance · RAG triad · Faithfulness","s":"A RAG system has two stages, and it can fail at either: retrieval might not find the relevant chunks, or generation might produce a bad answer even from good chunks. If you only look at the final answer, you can't tell which broke — so the cardinal rule of RAG evaluation is to measure retrieval and generation separately . Most RAG failures are actually retrieval failures (Lesson 8.1), and you'll never know unless you check retrieval on its own."},{"f":"sd-interview.html","t":"Interview check: System Design","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"What a system design interview tests · Rapid-fire check · Mock interview prompts · First move on any prompt? · Recommender / search design? · Why the funnel? · Recurring pattern? · Latency SLA? · Scale a service? · LLM serving? · Cost lever #1?","s":"System design is the interview that most separates senior from junior engineers, because it can't be crammed — it tests whether you can take a vague, open-ended problem and drive it to a coherent design while reasoning about scale, cost, and trade-offs out loud."},{"f":"sd1-framework.html","t":"How to approach an AI system design interview","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"System design tests judgment, not a memorized answer · Back-of-the-envelope estimation · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · no single right answer · Clarify first, always. · framework · Back-of-the-envelope estimation · Peak QPS · framework · QPS · AI system design interview · back-of-the-envelope estimation","s":"An AI system design interview asks you to architect a complete ML-powered system — \"design the recommendation feed for a video app,\" \"design a search engine,\" \"design an LLM assistant.\" Unlike a coding question, there's no single correct answer. The interviewer is testing your judgment : can you turn a vague prompt into concrete requirements, sketch a sensible architecture, reason about scale and cost, and discuss trade-offs out loud?"},{"f":"sd2-requirements.html","t":"Requirements & SLAs: latency, throughput, cost","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"Turning \"fast and cheap\" into numbers · SLAs and the tyranny of the tail · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Functional · non-functional · Latency · throughput · cost · latency budget · SLA · percentiles · Functional requirements · Latency · Throughput · percentiles · latency budget · p95 · tail · Cost · Non-functional requirements · p99 · SLA · requirements","s":"\"The system should be fast, cheap, and handle lots of users\" is not a design — it's a wish. The first real work of system design is turning vague desires into requirements precise enough to design against, split into two kinds. Functional requirements describe what the system does (\"recommend 10 videos,\" \"return search results\")."},{"f":"sd3-recsys.html","t":"Designing a recommendation system","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"The most common ML system design question · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · recommender · two-stage funnel · Candidate generation · recall · Ranking · precision · cost · two-stage funnel · Ranking · Candidate generation","s":"\"Design the recommendation feed\" — for videos, products, posts, music — is the single most common ML system design prompt, because recommenders are everywhere and they exercise every part of the framework. A recommendation system selects, from a huge catalog of items, the handful most likely to interest a specific user right now."},{"f":"sd4-search.html","t":"Designing a search / ranking system","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"Search is recommendation with a query · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · two-stage funnel · retrieval · ranking/reranking · query · Keyword retrieval · semantic retrieval · Hybrid retrieval · Semantic retrieval · query · inverted index · Keyword retrieval · hybrid retrieval · search / ranking system","s":"Designing a search / ranking system — \"design search for an e-commerce site,\" \"design a document search engine\" — is recommendation's close cousin, and it reuses the same two-stage funnel. The difference is the input: a recommender starts from a user profile (\"what would this person like?\"), while search starts from an explicit query (\"what matches these words?\")."},{"f":"sd5-ragscale.html","t":"Designing a RAG assistant at scale","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"RAG as a production system, not a demo · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · offline indexing · online serving · scale each independently · LLM input tokens · k · Reranking · caching · online serving path · RAG assistant at scale · offline indexing pipeline","s":"Track 8 taught how RAG works: retrieve relevant documents, then have an LLM generate a grounded answer. Building a RAG demo is a weekend project. Designing a RAG assistant at scale — serving millions of users over millions of documents, fast and affordably — is a system-design problem that combines everything so far."},{"f":"sd6-llmserving.html","t":"Designing an LLM serving platform","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"Serving an LLM is a different beast · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · huge · autoregressively · queue · batch scheduler · GPU worker pool · KV cache · Batching · KV caching · GPU workers · stream · KV cache · queue · batch scheduler · LLM serving platform","s":"Serving a classical model is one quick prediction per request. Serving a large language model is fundamentally harder, and understanding why is the key to designing an LLM serving platform — the infrastructure that makes large-model inference fast and affordable at scale. Two properties make LLMs special. First, they're huge : billions of parameters, so each forward pass is billions of operations and the model needs expensive GPU memory just to load."},{"f":"sd7-cost.html","t":"Caching, sharding & cost control","tn":"AI System Design","k":"11","x":"Cost is a first-class design goal · Sharding: when one machine isn't enough · Check yourself · Build the reasoning yourself · Cost · Caching · hit rate · exact-match · semantic · staleness · Sharding · router · semantic cache · Caching · sharding · hit rate · shard · router · exact-match cache","s":"An AI system that works but costs too much to run is a failed design. At scale — millions of requests, GPU inference, huge indexes — cost isn't an afterthought; it's a primary constraint you design against, alongside latency and correctness. This lesson covers the cross-cutting techniques that keep large AI systems fast and affordable, the two most important being caching (avoid repeated work) and sharding (split work that's too big for one machine)."}],"glossary":[{"term":"Vector","desc":"An ordered list of numbers; the basic way data and parameters are represented."},{"term":"Matrix","desc":"A grid of numbers; applying one is a linear transformation, and a matrix multiply is the core operation of ML."},{"term":"Gradient","desc":"The vector of partial derivatives — which way, and how steeply, a function increases; points the way to adjust parameters."},{"term":"Gradient descent","desc":"The learning algorithm: repeatedly step parameters opposite the gradient to reduce error."},{"term":"Learning rate","desc":"The size of each gradient-descent step; too big diverges, too small crawls."},{"term":"Probability distribution","desc":"A description of how likely each outcome is; models output and sample from these."},{"term":"Bayes' rule","desc":"How to update a belief given new evidence — the backbone of many ML methods."},{"term":"Maximum likelihood","desc":"Choosing parameters that make the observed data most probable; justifies common loss functions."},{"term":"Vectorization","desc":"Replacing Python loops with array operations (NumPy) so numerical code runs fast."},{"term":"Data leakage","desc":"When information from the test set (or the future) sneaks into training, inflating scores and ruining real performance."},{"term":"Supervised learning","desc":"Learning a mapping X → y from labeled examples."},{"term":"Overfitting","desc":"Fitting the training data so closely (including its noise) that the model fails on new data."},{"term":"Bias–variance tradeoff","desc":"Error splits into bias (too-simple/underfit) and variance (too-sensitive/overfit); complexity trades one for the other."},{"term":"Regularization","desc":"Penalizing complexity (L1/L2, dropout, early stopping) to reduce overfitting."},{"term":"Cross-validation","desc":"Rotating which fold is held out to estimate performance and tune without touching the test set."},{"term":"Precision","desc":"Of the items predicted positive, the fraction that truly were: TP/(TP+FP)."},{"term":"Recall","desc":"Of the actual positives, the fraction caught: TP/(TP+FN)."},{"term":"F1 score","desc":"The harmonic mean of precision and recall — a single balanced metric."},{"term":"Confusion matrix","desc":"The table of true/false positives and negatives from which precision and recall are computed."},{"term":"Ensemble","desc":"Combining many models (e.g., a random forest) so their independent errors cancel — lowering variance."},{"term":"Neuron","desc":"A weighted sum of inputs plus a bias, passed through a nonlinear activation."},{"term":"Activation function","desc":"The nonlinearity (ReLU, sigmoid, tanh, GELU) that lets stacked layers model complex patterns."},{"term":"Backpropagation","desc":"Computing every weight's gradient efficiently via the chain rule, in one backward pass."},{"term":"Vanishing gradients","desc":"When gradients shrink toward zero through many layers, so early layers barely learn; fixed by ReLU, good init, normalization, residual connections."},{"term":"CNN","desc":"Convolutional neural network — uses shared local filters, ideal for images (locality + translation invariance)."},{"term":"RNN","desc":"Recurrent neural network — processes sequences with a hidden state; largely superseded by transformers."},{"term":"Dropout","desc":"Randomly zeroing units during training to prevent co-adaptation — a regularizer."},{"term":"Transfer learning","desc":"Reusing a pretrained model and adapting only a small part to a new task — strong results from little data."},{"term":"Token","desc":"The unit of text a model processes (a word or word-piece); text is split into tokens before modeling."},{"term":"Embedding","desc":"A dense vector representing a token or item, where similar things are close together."},{"term":"Self-attention","desc":"Letting every position attend to every other via query-key-value, capturing long-range relationships directly."},{"term":"Transformer","desc":"The architecture built on stacked self-attention; the foundation of modern LLMs, prized for long-range modeling and parallelism."},{"term":"Positional encoding","desc":"Information added to inputs so the order-agnostic transformer knows token order."},{"term":"Context window","desc":"The maximum number of tokens a model can attend to at once — a hard limit on input and history."},{"term":"Pretraining","desc":"Learning language by predicting the next token on massive text — where an LLM gains its capability."},{"term":"RLHF","desc":"Reinforcement learning from human feedback — aligning a model with human preferences for helpfulness and safety."},{"term":"Fine-tuning","desc":"Further training a model on task-specific data to shape its behavior or style."},{"term":"LoRA","desc":"Low-Rank Adaptation — fine-tuning by training a tiny low-rank adapter while freezing the model; cheap and swappable."},{"term":"Prompting","desc":"Steering a fixed model at inference time via the input (few-shot examples, chain-of-thought)."},{"term":"Chain-of-thought","desc":"Prompting the model to reason step by step, which improves performance on hard problems."},{"term":"Temperature","desc":"A decoding knob for randomness — low for factual/precise output, high for creative."},{"term":"Hallucination","desc":"When a model confidently generates false information, because it optimizes plausibility, not truth."},{"term":"Quantization","desc":"Running a model at lower numerical precision to cut memory and speed up inference, with little accuracy loss."},{"term":"RAG","desc":"Retrieving relevant documents at query time and grounding the LLM's answer in them — for current, private, citable knowledge."},{"term":"Vector database","desc":"A store of embeddings with fast approximate nearest-neighbor search, powering retrieval."},{"term":"Chunking","desc":"Splitting documents into passages before embedding; you can only retrieve what your chunks contain."},{"term":"Recall@k","desc":"Whether the relevant chunk is among the top-k retrieved — the key retrieval metric for RAG."},{"term":"Reranking","desc":"A second, precise pass (often a cross-encoder) that reorders retrieved candidates for quality."},{"term":"Hybrid search","desc":"Combining semantic (embedding) and keyword (BM25) retrieval so exact terms and meaning are both covered."},{"term":"Faithfulness","desc":"Whether a generated answer is actually grounded in the retrieved context (vs hallucinated)."},{"term":"Train/serve skew","desc":"Features computed differently at training vs serving time — a silent accuracy killer."},{"term":"Agent","desc":"An LLM in a loop that reasons, calls tools, observes results, and repeats to accomplish multi-step tasks."},{"term":"Tool use / function calling","desc":"Letting a model emit a structured request that your code executes — search, code, an API."},{"term":"ReAct","desc":"Interleaving Thought → Action → Observation so tool use is deliberate and the trace is debuggable."},{"term":"Guardrails","desc":"Independent checks around a model (permission allowlists, budgets, human approval) that enforce safety regardless of the model."},{"term":"Prompt injection","desc":"Malicious instructions hidden in content a model reads, attempting to hijack it — an unsolved security problem."},{"term":"Least privilege","desc":"Giving a system only the minimum access it needs, so a compromised agent can't cause serious harm."},{"term":"MLOps","desc":"The engineering of deploying, serving, monitoring, and maintaining ML in production — the lifecycle loop."},{"term":"Feature store","desc":"A system that computes and serves features consistently for both training and serving, preventing skew."},{"term":"Model registry","desc":"A versioned catalog of trained models with staged promotion and instant rollback."},{"term":"Serving","desc":"Running a packaged model so it answers prediction requests — online (real-time), batch, or streaming."},{"term":"Latency vs throughput","desc":"Time for one request vs total requests handled — online serving optimizes the first, batch the second."},{"term":"Drift","desc":"When live data moves away from the training distribution, silently degrading a deployed model; fixed by retraining."},{"term":"Autoscaling","desc":"Automatically adjusting the number of serving replicas with traffic — enough at peak, no waste off-peak."},{"term":"Two-stage funnel","desc":"Cheap wide retrieval then expensive narrow ranking — how recommenders and search scale."},{"term":"QPS","desc":"Queries per second — the request rate a system must handle, sized for the peak, not the average."},{"term":"Caching","desc":"Reusing stored results for repeated requests; savings scale with the hit rate."},{"term":"Goodhart's law","desc":"When a measure becomes the target, it stops being a good measure — the trap of optimizing a single proxy."},{"term":"Offline vs online evaluation","desc":"Testing on a fixed dataset (fast proxy) vs A/B testing on real users (ground truth)."},{"term":"A/B test","desc":"A randomized experiment comparing a new system against the current one on live traffic."},{"term":"LLM-as-judge","desc":"Using a capable model to grade outputs at scale — validated against human labels first."},{"term":"Disparate impact","desc":"When a model's outcomes disproportionately harm a group; the four-fifths rule is a common red-flag check."},{"term":"Red-teaming","desc":"Deliberately attacking your own system to find failures and jailbreaks before real adversaries do."},{"term":"PII","desc":"Personally Identifiable Information — data that must be minimized, protected, and often redacted."},{"term":"Reproducibility","desc":"Getting the same result again by pinning code, data, environment, and the random seed."},{"term":"Image tensor","desc":"An image as a height x width x channels grid of pixel numbers — all a model ever sees."},{"term":"Convolution","desc":"Sliding a small learned filter over an image to detect a pattern anywhere it appears (weight sharing)."},{"term":"Feature map","desc":"The output of a convolution — where in the image a given filter's pattern was found."},{"term":"Data augmentation","desc":"Random flips, crops, rotations, and color shifts that turn one image into many, improving generalization."},{"term":"Object detection","desc":"Localizing and classifying each object — a bounding box plus a class label per object."},{"term":"IoU","desc":"Intersection over Union — overlap area / union area of two boxes; a detection usually counts as correct at IoU >= 0.5."},{"term":"Segmentation","desc":"Assigning a class to every pixel — the finest-grained vision task, giving exact shapes (semantic vs instance)."},{"term":"U-Net","desc":"An encoder-decoder with skip connections: compress to understand, expand to localize; used for masks and diffusion denoising."},{"term":"Vision Transformer (ViT)","desc":"A transformer that treats image patches as tokens — 'an image is worth 16x16 words'."},{"term":"Inductive bias","desc":"Assumptions built into an architecture; CNNs bake in locality/translation-invariance, ViTs assume less and need more data."},{"term":"Diffusion model","desc":"A generator that learns to reverse noising: denoise from pure noise into a new image (Stable Diffusion, DALL-E)."},{"term":"Latent diffusion","desc":"Running diffusion in a compressed latent space (not raw pixels) to make text-to-image fast."},{"term":"CLIP","desc":"A model that aligns images and text in one shared embedding space via contrastive learning — enabling zero-shot classification."},{"term":"Multimodal / VLM","desc":"A model working across data types (images + text); modern vision-language models feed image tokens into an LLM."}]};
